{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480459"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:43:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:43:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"54"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"54","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/54"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.43,0.1,0.02,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"54"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71642"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"54","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/54"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"54"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57138"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2956"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7032"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42956"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71642"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with new onset palpitations. He has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, diabetic nephropathy and stage 4 chronic kidney disease with an estimated creatinine clearance of 22 mL/min. He takes regular medications for these conditions. He has no history of cerebrovascular events or valvular heart disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits except for an irregular pulse of 150/min. An electrocardiogram shows an irregularly irregular rhythm with a ventricular rate of 150/min and absent P waves. To control his tachycardia, metoprolol 25 mg twice daily is prescribed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate anticoagulation strategy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dual antiplatelet therapy","Warfarin","Unfractionated heparin","No anticoagulation","Apixaban 5 mg twice daily"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has non-valvular atrial fibrillation. Non-valvular atrial fibrillation refers to AF in patients who do not have moderate or severe mitral stenosis or a mechanical heart valve. The guidelines recommend all patients with non-valvular AF should be anticoagulated unless they have a very high bleeding risk or a very low risk of stroke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo calculate the risk of stroke, the CHA2DS2-VA scoring system is used. Based on trials performed, the evidence is:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor men and women with score of 0, anticoagulant therapy is not recommended\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor men and women with score of 1, oral anticoagulation should be considered\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor men and women with score of 2 or more, there is much benefit with oral anticoagulants and thus should be prescribed. This patient has a score of 3 and thus anticoagulation must be prescribed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDual antiplatelet therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended to prevent thromboembolic events in patients with AF as it is less effective than anticoagulation and carries a similar bleeding risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice in this case. While direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) are generally first-line for non-valvular AF due to their predictable dose response and lack of monitoring requirements, they are contraindicated in severe renal impairment. This patient\u0027s creatinine clearance of 22 mL/min makes warfarin the safest option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnfractionated heparin\u003C/strong\u003E would only be appropriate for initial bridging anticoagulation in the acute hospital setting. It is not suitable for long-term outpatient management of AF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo anticoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given this patient\u0027s CHA2DS2-VA score of 3 (age \u003E65, hypertension, diabetes) puts him at high risk of stroke. The benefits of anticoagulation clearly outweigh the risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in patients with creatinine clearance less than 25 mL/min due to lack of safety data and risk of drug accumulation. While it would otherwise be an excellent choice for AF anticoagulation, this patient\u0027s renal function precludes its use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Warfarin is the anticoagulant of choice for patients with stage 4 chronic kidney disease and atrial fibrillation.","Direct oral anticoagulants are contraindicated in severe renal impairment with creatinine clearance \u003C25 mL/min.","CHA2DS2-VA score guides anticoagulation decisions in atrial fibrillation, with scores \u22652 strongly indicating anticoagulation."],"references":["Brieger D, Amerena J, Attia J, et al. National Heart Foundation of Australia and the Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Australian Clinical Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Atrial Fibrillation 2018. Heart, Lung Circ. 2018; 27:1209-66."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57138"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"54"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57138"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T00:50:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T00:52:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"54"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71642"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount